Diagnosis.

Elachistocleis cesarii

is recognized by the following combination of characters: 
1
) ventral coloration is white or yellow with gray marks and reticulations; 
2
) presence of postcommisural glands behind the corner of mouth; 
3
) tympanum concealed; 
4
) advertisement call with the mean dominant frequency of about 
3.5
kHz.

Variation. Females are larger than males (see
Table 1
). Females present variation in size, with the SVL varying from 19.4 up to 42.7 mm (
Thomé & Brasileiro, 2007
). The vertebral stripe may be absent. The ventral spots may not reach the flanks and the groin region of some individuals. The throat of males is darker than that of females.

Geographical distribution. Besides the localities of the type series, the species is known in the municipalities of Rio Claro, Campinas, Itirapina, São Paulo, Angatuba, and Ubatuba, all in the state of São Paulo. In the state of Minas Gerais it can be found in the municipalities of Jaboticatubas, Santana do Riacho, Munhoz, and Viçosa. In the state of Goiás it can be found in Pontalina (
Figure 5
).
